Kubernetes is the industry‑standard platform for container orchestration — it automates the deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications (like those built with Docker). Think of it as the “operating system of the cloud” for containers.

🔑 Key Concepts
Cluster → A set of machines (nodes) running Kubernetes.

Node → A worker machine (VM or physical) where containers run.

Pod → The smallest deployable unit; usually runs one container (or tightly coupled ones).

Deployment → Defines how many replicas of a pod should run and manages rolling updates.

Service → Provides stable networking and load balancing for pods.

Ingress → Manages external access (HTTP/HTTPS) to services.

ConfigMap / Secret → Store configuration and sensitive data separately from code.

⚙️ How Kubernetes Works (Real‑Time Flow)
Developer pushes code → Jenkins builds Docker image.

Image stored in registry → Docker Hub, AWS ECR, GCP Artifact Registry.

Kubernetes Deployment → Pulls image from registry.

Pods created → Containers run inside pods across cluster nodes.

Service exposes pods → Provides stable IP and load balancing.

Ingress routes traffic → External users access the app.

Autoscaling & Self‑Healing → Kubernetes adds/removes pods based on demand, restarts failed ones.

🚫 Common Errors in Real Projects
ImagePullBackOff → Kubernetes can’t pull image (wrong tag/registry auth).

CrashLoopBackOff → Container keeps crashing (bad config, missing env vars).

Pending Pods → No resources available on nodes.

Service not reachable → Misconfigured networking or firewall.

RBAC errors → Insufficient permissions for service accounts.

🗣️ Interview Narration Tip

“In real projects, Kubernetes pulls Docker images built by Jenkins, runs them as pods, and exposes them via services and ingress. It automatically scales based on demand and restarts failed pods. This makes deployments reliable, scalable, and cloud‑native.”

✅ Bottom Line: Kubernetes is the backbone of modern cloud deployments, ensuring apps are scalable, resilient, and portable.
📦 Deployment & Pods
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml → Create/update resources from YAML

kubectl get pods → List all pods

kubectl describe pod <pod-name> → Detailed pod info (events, status)

kubectl logs <pod-name> → View pod logs

kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- bash → Open shell inside pod

🌐 Services & Networking
kubectl get svc → List services

kubectl describe svc <service-name> → Inspect service details

kubectl port-forward svc/myapp 8080:80 → Forward local port to service

kubectl get ingress → List ingress rules

kubectl describe ingress <ingress-name> → Inspect ingress routing

⚙️ Scaling & Updates
kubectl scale deployment myapp-deployment --replicas=5 → Scale pods

kubectl rollout status deployment/myapp-deployment → Check rollout progress

kubectl rollout undo deployment/myapp-deployment → Rollback to previous version

kubectl set image deployment/myapp-deployment myapp-container=myrepo/myapp:v2 → Update container image

🔍 Cluster & Node Management
kubectl get nodes → List cluster nodes

kubectl describe node <node-name> → Node details (resources, labels)

kubectl top nodes → Resource usage (CPU/memory)

kubectl top pods → Pod resource usage

🛠️ Debugging & Troubleshooting
kubectl get events → Show cluster events (failures, scheduling issues)

kubectl describe deployment myapp-deployment → Inspect deployment issues

kubectl get pod <pod-name> -o yaml → Full YAML definition for debugging

kubectl delete pod <pod-name> → Kill pod (Kubernetes will restart it)

