⚠️ Kubernetes Troubleshooting Flow
1. Pod Pending
Cause: No resources on nodes, wrong nodeSelector, or taints.

Fix:

Check nodes → kubectl get nodes

Inspect events → kubectl describe pod <pod>

Add resources or adjust scheduling rules.

2. ImagePullBackOff
Cause: Wrong image name/tag, private registry without credentials.

Fix:

Verify image → kubectl describe pod <pod>

Check registry login → kubectl create secret docker-registry

Correct image tag in Deployment YAML.

3. CrashLoopBackOff
Cause: Container keeps crashing (bad command, missing env vars, app error).

Fix:

View logs → kubectl logs <pod>

Debug shell → kubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash

Fix entrypoint or configuration.

4. Service Not Reachable
Cause: Wrong port mapping, selector mismatch, or firewall rules.

Fix:

Inspect service → kubectl describe svc <service>

Verify pod labels match service selector.

Use kubectl port-forward for quick testing.

5. Ingress Errors
Cause: Misconfigured rules, DNS not pointing, missing ingress controller.

Fix:

Check ingress → kubectl describe ingress <ingress>

Ensure NGINX/Traefik ingress controller is running.

Verify DNS resolves to cluster IP.

6. RBAC / Permission Errors
Cause: Service account lacks required roles.

Fix:

Inspect roles → kubectl describe rolebinding

Grant permissions with Role/ClusterRoleBinding.

🧠 Interview Narration Tip
“When troubleshooting Kubernetes, I follow a flow: check pod status, inspect events, look at logs, and verify service/ingress configurations. Most errors fall into categories like scheduling issues, image pulls, container crashes, networking misconfigurations, or RBAC problems. Using kubectl describe, logs, and exec systematically helps isolate and fix issues quickly.”

✅ Bottom Line: Kubernetes troubleshooting is about categorizing errors → checking logs/events → applying fixes. This structured approach shows interviewers you can handle real‑world cluster issues.

